We did agree the design in the #1147 PR. In short it is this: 
1. Support current style:
```
Execute JavaScript
...    element = arguments[0];
...    original_style = element.getAttribute('style');
...    element.setAttribute('style', original_style + "; background: yellow;");
...    setTimeout(function(){
...       element.setAttribute('style', original_style);
...    }, 300);
```
2. Support arguments in the end:
```
Execute Javascript
...    element = arguments[0];
...    original_style = element.getAttribute('style');
...    element.setAttribute('style', original_style + "; background: yellow;");
...    setTimeout(function(){
...       element.setAttribute('style', original_style);
...    }, 300);
...    ARGUMENTS
...    ${element}    ${unused_arg}
```
3. Support changing the order of arguments and code:
```
Execute Javascript
...    ARGUMENTS
...    ${element}    ${unused_arg}
...    JAVASCRIPT
...    element = arguments[0];
...    original_style = element.getAttribute('style');
...    element.setAttribute('style', original_style + "; background: yellow;");
...    setTimeout(function(){
...       element.setAttribute('style', original_style);
...    }, 300);
```
4. Support defining the JAVASCRIPT at start (optional)
```
Execute Javascript
...    JAVASCRIPT
...    element = arguments[0];
...    original_style = element.getAttribute('style');
...    element.setAttribute('style', original_style + "; background: yellow;");
...    setTimeout(function(){
...       element.setAttribute('style', original_style);
...    }, 300);
...    ARGUMENTS
...    ${element}    ${unused_arg}
```
For more details see the discussion in #1147

@robert-kisteleki Ah, interesting. Hm, I have to say that my intuition here is still to leave as is. You have a point that there may be some rational in storing the entire error response, but in the majority of cases it'll be vastly more useful to just store a response error type, message, and code (say for running analytics on the most common types of errors that you run into). 

Even where that's not the case, you're probably better off persisting the body as JSON instead of a string (i.e. into a Postgres jsonb field or a Mongo document), so `json_body` will still be more useful there.

Admittedly there are some cases of course (like your own) where none of the above is desirable, but for these I'd tentatively recommend just re-serializing what you see in `json_body`. There's some performance impact here, but hopefully your stack isn't seeing all that many errors back from Stripe, and dumping/loading JSON is one of the faster things that you can do in a Python stack.

